
[1]retort

   RETORT', v.t. [L. retortus, retorqueo; re and torqueo, to throw.]

   1. To throw back; to reverberate.

   And they retort that beat again to the first giver.

   2. To return an argument, accusation, censure or incivility; as, to
   retort the charge of vanity.

   He pass'd through hostile scorn; and with retorted scorn, his back he
   turn'd.

   3. To bend or curve back; as a retorted line.

   RETORT', v.i. To return an argument or charge; to make a severe reply.
                He retorted upon his adversary with severity.

                                 RETORT', n.

   1. The return of an argument, charge or incivility in reply; as the
   retort courteous.

   2. In chimistry, a spherical vessel with its neck bent, to which the
   receiver is fitted; used in distillation.
